04428nmm a2200637Ia 9780520390829DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203908297 a10.1525/97805203908292doi  a(DE-B1597)642445  a(OCoLC)1380733247  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHD9490.C272b.S354 2023 7aHIS0410002bisacsh04a338.2/728209729223/eng/202302271 aSchields, Chelsea, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOffshore Attachments :bOil and Intimacy in the Caribbean /cChelsea Schields. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: “Oil Is the Lubricant” -- t1. Crude Bargains: Sex and the Making of an Oil Economy -- t2. Diminishing Returns: Domesticity on the Edge of Whiteness -- t3. Manufacturing Surplus: Population and Development in the Downstream -- t4. “Sexuality, Yes! Slavery, No!”: Erotic Rebellion and Economic Freedom -- t5. Dutch Diseases: Race, Welfare, and the Quantification of Kinship -- tConclusion: Acts of Attachment -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOffshore Attachments reveals how the contested management of sex and race transformed the Caribbean into a crucial site in the global oil economy. By the mid-twentieth century, the Dutch islands of Curaçao and Aruba housed the world’s largest oil refineries. To bolster this massive industrial experiment, oil corporations and political authorities offshored intimacy, circumventing laws regulating sex, reproduction, and the family in a bid to maximize profits and turn Caribbean subjects into citizens. Historian Chelsea Schields demonstrates how Caribbean people both embraced and challenged efforts to alter intimate behavior in service to the energy economy. Moving from Caribbean oil towns to European metropolises and examining such issues as sex work, contraception, kinship, and the constitution of desire, Schields narrates a surprising story of how racialized concern with sex shaped hydrocarbon industries as the age of oil met the end of empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aIntimacy (Psychology). 0aOil industrieszCaribbean Areay20th century. 0aSex workerszCaribbean Areay20th century. 0aSexzCaribbean Areay20th century. 7aHISTORY / Caribbean & West Indies / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520390829?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520390829423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520390829/original  a978-3-11-079134-1  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131913-1  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2023  aZDB-23-DGGb2023